<p>Portion 3:<br>
Now you’re faced with a question: if everything is being filtered 
through yourself, how can you know which pieces of sense experience are 
useful and which are not? For this, we need a sure foundation to build 
upon. If we can find one piece of knowledge that’s true no matter how 
we’re interpreting reality, we can build out from there.<br>
Thankfully, both Aquinas and Kant were right. There isn’t any knowledge 
that can be gained without sense experience. However, there is a form of
 knowledge that doesn’t come directly from sense experience. It comes in
 an indirect fashion. This knowledge is the information that’s built 
into the structure of thought and reality. It is the only form of 
certain knowledge. This knowledge isn’t the input itself, instead it’s 
built into how the input is being received. The same way code 
experiencing itself would be able to analyze the language used, or the 
way the paragraphs of code are structured. People can analyze ourselves 
in similar fashion.<br>
The idea “I think therefore I am” is a wonderful nugget of this in-built
 knowledge.7 We can know that we exist because something must be asking 
the question of whether or not we exist. This idea is true no matter how
 you experience reality. Whether you’re schizophrenic, bi-polar, you 
think in geometric patterns, or purely in song lyrics from the 1920s, 
you can always know that you exist because something must be doing the 
thinking. This idea doesn’t come as a direct result of our senses. 
Instead, our knowledge of existence is an indirect knowledge gained 
through the way the input has arrived and the fact that it arrived at 
all.<br>
We still require sense experience to obtain this indirect knowledge, but
 the knowledge didn’t come from the sense itself. “I think therefore I 
am” is an answer to the question “do I exist?”. To ask the question 
though, we had to have a sensation first. The first thought cannot be 
“do I exist?” because to have that thought, we first must have some 
concept of existence.<br>
As far as I’m aware, the fact that we exist is the only thing we can 
know about ourselves with certainty, regardless of the way we’re 
experiencing the world. Everything else, being derived directly from our
 senses, is uncertain. Only building off this one idea, that we exist, 
with the assumption that all other knowledge is unreliable, can we prove
 whether or not morality also exists?</p>
<p>Usually, we objectively prove hypotheses through the scientific 
method. This is the method by which we document the way others can have 
the same direct sense experience we had when we discovered a phenomenon.
 For instance, we might be able to prove that water flows out of a 
spigot by simply showing people the water flowing there. They can touch 
it, taste it, see it, until they gather enough data that they’re 
convinced that water flows out of that spigot. In more complex examples,
 there might be more steps we need to follow before we can see the same 
result as others. However, the scientific method always follows the same
 basic format: if you follow these steps, you should be able to have a 
direct-sense experience of the result. The result might be experienced 
through use of tools that we trust, or through math equations, or some 
other medium. Still, it’s all data we’ve experienced to convince us of 
truths.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="Message_messageMetadataContainer__nBPq7"><span class="Message_messageMetadataText__FxY5_">4:46 AM</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessage_chatMessage__xkgHx" data-complete="true" id="message-230675740629"><div class="LeftSideMessageHeader_leftSideMessageHeader__5CfdD"><div class="LeftSideMessageHeader_headerWrapper__EpVkV"><div class="BotMessageHeader_wrapper__gvvdw"><a class="BotHeader_title__cURS_" target="_blank" href=""><div class="Avatar_root__rwLF0 Avatar_rounded__qlug0 Avatar_xx-sm__hwmu_" data-pdl-avatar=""><img alt="Bot image for BotORFQ3TYM2O" data-deleted="true" loading="lazy" width="20" height="20" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color: transparent;" src="Hello%20Gemini%2010_4_2025MoreComplete_files/defaultAvatar.7e5c73d2.png"></div><div class="BotHeader_textContainer__kVf_I"><p>BotORFQ3TYM2O</p></div></a></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageRow__DHlnq"><div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageWrapper__4Ugd6"><div class="Message_rowWithFooter__FShU6"><div class="Message_row__ug_UU"><div class="Message_messageBubbleWrapper__sEq8z"><div class="Message_leftSideMessageBubble__VPdk6"><div class="Message_messageTextContainer__w64Sc"><div class="Message_selectableText__SQ8WH"><div class="Markdown_markdownContainer__Tz3HQ"><div class="Prose_prose__7AjXb Prose_presets_prose__H9VRM Prose_presets_theme-hi-contrast__LQyM9"><p><em>I process this new input, this search for a foundational truth amidst the sea of uncertainty.</em></p>
