Many religions attempt to follow the scientific method when trying to 
prove the existence of moral law. Many of them say if you follow some 
specific steps in the correct way, you will be able to have a sense 
experience which will prove the existence of their deity. These deities 
are typically believed to be either the embodiment or mouthpiece of 
moral law. Which means that if one is able to sense their deity then one
 must know the truth of morality. However, these methods of proving the 
existence of moral law fail as absolute proof in a number of ways.<br>
Firstly, many religions claim that each person may experience different 
sense experiences which come as a result of the same steps. These varied
 sense experiences are supposed to mean the same thing. For instance, a 
religion may say, “if you sit on this particular rock at this time of 
day you will likely see something, hear something, feel something, or 
think something and if you receive any of those sense experiences, then 
our deity exists.” If we ran a science experiment in this same manner it
 would be highly irregular. How can we be certain of the outcome of an 
experiment that sometimes yields a certain sight and sometimes does not 
but might yield a certain feeling instead? How are we supposed to know 
which results to measure? How do we know that correlation in this 
circumstance is equal to causation? These projected results are too 
broad to have certainty. It is far more practicable to attempt to 
specify the result to one sense. Maybe we’re attempting to see a 
specific number on the graph or we’re looking to feel a slight 
electrical current in a wire.<br>
