 results gained by the scientific method are experienced subjectively by
 individual researchers. This is important because it allows room for 
human error. Not just in the morality experiment, but in any scientific 
experiment we ever conduct. In calling something objective fact, we are 
hoping that the great majority of people have sensed things correctly 
and are being honest.<br>
Hopefully, a color-blind researcher could trust the experience of seeing
 most people agree that a flower is purple. However, if they wanted to 
