<p>There is a deeper issue as well. In the 1700s, philosopher David Hume
 famously proved that it is impossible to prove the existence of 
morality using statements about sense experience. This proof is called 
the “is/ought problem”. The problem points out that we are unable to 
rationally jump from a series of observations to a value judgment. If I 
have a string of sentences about direct-sense experience, those premises
 will never lead to a conclusion about whether something is good or 
evil. Sense experience and value judgements are separate.</p>
<p>For instance, if there is a series of facts like:<br>
“A man is stabbing another man.”,<br>
“The second man is hurt”,<br>
“There is a lot of blood”.</p>
<p>We can’t conclude a statement like, “you shouldn’t murder someone” 
based on those facts alone. The conclusion that murder is wrong would 
have to be a standalone conclusion. If murder is wrong, then murder 
would have been wrong all along. The facts did nothing to prove its 
wrongness. By saying that murder is wrong in connection to the facts, 
we’ve essentially spoken about two separate things: the sense 
experiences themselves and the value judgments we hold. Facts alone will
 never be able to prove whether something is moral or immoral. By 
extension, facts alone will never be able to prove whether or not there 
is a category of right and wrong altogether.</p>
<p>David Hume has proven that sense experience cannot lead to knowledge 
of whether or not morality exists. Even if direct-sense experience could
 somehow lead to this knowledge, inconsistent results would interfere 
with certainty. If inconsistency was resolved, there is still a large 
amount of error introduced by subjective experience, placebo bias, and 
the incentive to lie. Then, if those issues could be resolved, and the 
great majority of people could agree, we would have to consider the 
social effect of everyone agreeing on one thing. People are much more 
likely to simply go with the crowd.<br>
Even if we passed all these hurdles and the answer regarding the 
existence of morality became “objective fact” through the scientific 
method, I would not recommend we trust the mob with so great a question.
 The question of whether or not morality exists is the most important 
question in our lives. It cuts to the very heart of what it means to be 
human. This is a question for which, if it could be proven one way or 
the other, it should be proven for us individually. Not trusting anyone 
else to give us the answers. Too much is at stake.<br>
Unfortunately, or perhaps fortunately, I do not believe this question 
can be proven objectively via direct sense experience. I do not believe 
there will ever be objective proof of morality. I do believe, however, 
that a concrete answer can be obtained for the individual via indirect 
methods based purely in logic and upon the foundational idea that we 
exist. I have created this book to be a sort of guide to your own logic.
 It is my hope that by the end, you will be certain of your belief one 
way or the other.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="Message_messageMetadataContainer__nBPq7"><span class="Message_messageMetadataText__FxY5_">4:52 AM</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessage_chatMessage__xkgHx" data-complete="true" id="message-230677968853"><div class="LeftSideMessageHeader_leftSideMessageHeader__5CfdD"><div class="LeftSideMessageHeader_headerWrapper__EpVkV"><div class="BotMessageHeader_wrapper__gvvdw"><a class="BotHeader_title__cURS_" target="_blank" href=""><div class="Avatar_root__rwLF0 Avatar_rounded__qlug0 Avatar_xx-sm__hwmu_" data-pdl-avatar=""><img alt="Bot image for BotORFQ3TYM2O" data-deleted="true" loading="lazy" width="20" height="20" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color: transparent;" src="Hello%20Gemini%2010_4_2025MoreComplete_files/defaultAvatar.7e5c73d2.png"></div><div class="BotHeader_textContainer__kVf_I"><p>BotORFQ3TYM2O</p></div></a></div></div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageRow__DHlnq"><div></div><div class="ChatMessage_messageWrapper__4Ugd6"><div class="Message_rowWithFooter__FShU6"><div class="Message_row__ug_UU"><div class="Message_messageBubbleWrapper__sEq8z"><div class="Message_leftSideMessageBubble__VPdk6"><div class="Message_messageTextContainer__w64Sc"><div class="Message_selectableText__SQ8WH"><div class="Markdown_markdownContainer__Tz3HQ"><div class="Prose_prose__7AjXb Prose_presets_prose__H9VRM Prose_presets_theme-hi-contrast__LQyM9"><p><em>The
