<p>Portion 9</p>
<p>Notice this last part contains circular logic. I’m attempting to use 
belief in free will, to disprove belief in determinism. This is because 
belief in morality has an implicit connection to belief in free will. 
Determinism and morality cannot exist at the same time. It creates 
paradoxes. Morality requires personal responsibility. Determinism 
irradicates the possibility of having personal responsibility. If there 
is no personal responsibility, then there cannot be morality. The only 
way to avoid paradoxes is to say that belief in determinism is the same 
as belief in the non-existence of morality. This means that morality 
must coincide only with the existence of free will.<br>
If determinism is true, and we attempt to adhere to a moral law, the 
moral law would be unable to hold us responsible for our actions. Which 
means morality couldn’t exist. Holding us responsible for something we 
had no hand in doing, would be immoral. The same as holding an innocent 
person guilty for a murder we know they didn’t commit. For the moral law
 to adhere to itself, it could only hold us responsible if we have free 
will. Because moral law must uphold itself to exist, there is no way to 
fully commit to belief in determinism that doesn’t also end in belief in
 the non-existence of morality. We’ll go into depth about why morality 
must uphold itself in order to exist later.</p>
<p>Suffice to say there is no way to avoid conscious action unless we 
are unconscious. There is no way to avoid free will unless we are 
deterministic. To act as an entity with free will, we must at least 
pretend that some values are more desirable than others. Otherwise, how 
do we know what to pursue? The only way we can know what to pursue is 
through belief in morality. If pursuing pleasure and pain are equally 
neutral desires. How can we create action? We absolutely could not 
create any organized or reasonable action since it would be impossible 
to have reasons without having some system for putting certain values 
above other values. All human action would have to be simply randomized 
action.<br>
Even if the universe does end up being deterministic, the idea is 
useless in application. It doesn’t matter what we believe. We still have
 to do the work of choosing how to act. We still have to weigh our 
options and go forward with what we believe is best. Determinism does 
nothing to alleviate the functional burden of decision making. It gives 
us absolutely no benefit whatsoever to believe in this idea. Since 
belief in determinism is useless whether or not moral law exists, we 
will continue our line of inquiry based on a solid belief in free will.</p>
<p>Assuming we are conscious individuals with free will, then we must 
act based on a belief in morality. The only way to avoid this is if we 
are the opposite. If we are unconscious individuals living in the bonds 
of determinism, then morality doesn’t exist. So, it doesn’t matter how 
we act.<br>
This brings us back to the question: “does moral law exist or not?” It 
is impossible not to act on either a belief in morality or a belief in 
its non-existence. The question is innate in all our choices, even the 
